<span class="displaytext"><b>for immediate release<br/>contact:</b> kevin madden (857) 288-6390 <p><b>boston, ma –</b> today, (candidate last) for president launched its newest television ad, "everywhere." the ad features governor (candidate last) talking with the american people about the challenges confronting our country and the need to change washington. with an exceptional record of turning around businesses and institutions, governor (candidate last) is the one candidate prepared to meet today's challenges. together, he believes we can grow the economy, stop illegal immigration, defend life and preserve our traditional values. with his experience, vision and values, governor (candidate last) will make washington work again and build a brighter future for america. </p><p>the ad will begin airing today as part of the campaign's rotation in iowa. script and viewing links are below. </p><p><b> <u>script for "everywhere" (tv:30):</u> </b> </p><p><b>governor (candidate full):</b> "everywhere my family and i go we hear that america's challenges are simply too big for washington politicians. </p><p>"i've spent my life tackling big problems – helping turn around business, the olympics, and state government. </p><p>"together we can grow our economy, stop illegal immigration, defend life and preserve the values that make america the hope of the earth. </p><p>"it's time to turn around washington. </p><p>"i'm (candidate full), and i approve this message." </p><p><em>to watch "everywhere," please see:</em> <a href="http://tv.(candidate full).com/?showid=728429">http://tv.(candidate full).com/?showid=728429</a> </p><p><u> <b>ad facts: script for "everywhere" (tv:30):</b> </u> </p><p><b>governor (candidate full):</b> "everywhere my family and i go we hear that america's challenges are simply too big for washington politicians. i've spent my life tackling big problems - helping turn around business, the olympics, and state government." </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- <em>bloomberg</em>:</b> '(candidate last)'s business record is unmatched by the current crop of leading candidates. at bain &amp; co., a boston management- consulting firm, he founded bain capital llc in 1984, which has grown into one of the nation's five largest private-equity firms. bain currently has $40 billion in assets under management, according to its web site.' (heidi pryzbyla, '(candidate last) finds classmate bush's management lapses unlikely hurdle,' <em>bloomberg</em>, 7/1/07) </p><p><b>- <em>fortune</em>:</b> "he is, after all, the most serious major-party presidential candidate to come out of the business world since ... well, since his father, george (candidate last), onetime ceo of american motors, who ran in 1968." (marcia vickers, "the (PARTY NAME)s' mr. fix-it," <em>fortune magazine</em>, 6/27/07) </p><p><b>- <em>the boston globe</em>'s robert gavin and sacha pfeiffer:</b> "in time, (candidate last) would lead the shaky start-up from a staff of seven people managing $37 million to 115 people managing $4 billion in assets. during (candidate last)'s 15-year tenure, bain capital would post an astonishing record, on average doubling its return on realized investments every year." (robert gavin and sacha pfeiffer, "reaping profit in study, sweat," <em>the boston globe</em>, 6/26/07) </p><p><b>- <em>the associated press</em>:</b> "(candidate last) took over as head of salt lake's olympic organizing committee in february 1999 after it was revealed salt lake organizers doled out more than $1 million in cash and gifts to members of the international olympic committee to win the 2002 bid. under (candidate last)'s leadership, the games were lauded as a critical success, a model of post-sept. 11 security and turned a $100 million profit. (candidate last), a successful venture capitalist before the games, wrote a book after titled 'turnaround: crisis, leadership and the olympic games.'" (debbie hummel, "utah's 'adopted son' returns to state for presidential fundraiser," <em>the associated press</em>, 2/21/07) </p><p><b>- <em>portfolio</em>'s matthew cooper:</b> "when (candidate last) took over the salt lake organizing committee in 1999, the games were a scandal-plagued fiscal wreck. he made them profitable." (matthew cooper, 'please, not another m.b.a. president,' <em>portfolio</em>, september 2007) </p><p><b>- <em>the weekly standard</em>'s terry eastland:</b> "as governor, (candidate last) has scored another turnaround, conservative in both ends and means. told during the campaign that he would inherit a deficit of between $500 million and $1.5 billion, (candidate last) discovered upon taking office a $650 million deficit in fiscal 2003 and an anticipated one of $3 billion in fiscal 2004. (candidate last) balanced the 2003 budget, and he finished 2004 with a $700 million surplus. a reviving economy helped, but (candidate last) didn't tax or borrow, and he reduced spending through government consolidation and reform." (terry eastland, "in 2008, will it be mormon in america?" <em>the weekly standard</em>, 6/6/05) </p><p><b>- in massachusetts, governor (candidate last) closed a nearly $3 billion shortfall without raising taxes.</b> "when (candidate full) became governor of massachusetts in 2003, the state had a budget gap of almost $3 billion and was losing thousands of jobs a month. in mr. (candidate last)'s four-year tenure, the deficit was eliminated without raising the sales tax or the income tax, and since the labor slump hit bottom in december 2003, the state has gained 81,000 jobs." (pam belluck, "(candidate last) candidacy puts massachusetts economy in spotlight," <em>the new york times</em>, 3/16/07) </p></blockquote> <p><b>governor (candidate full):</b> "together we can grow our economy, stop illegal immigration, defend life and preserve the values that make america the hope of the earth. it's time to turn around washington. i'm (candidate full), and i approve this message." </p><blockquote 